				<div class="post text">
				
					<div class="narrow">
					    
                        
						<div class="title">
							<h1>Shutdown letdown, but what&#8217;s next?</h1>						
						</div>
                        
						
						<div class="caption">
						
						<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/8d4a564c18973230e14bb7b8c38ef2e8/tumblr_inline_mu0oqfPZp71snsdec.png"/></p>
<p><em>"We have the best government that money can buy."</em></p>
<p><em>-Mark Twain</em></p>

<p>Wasn&#8217;t this supposed to happen several months ago, but we somehow put aside our differences and made it work?  Oh right, we agreed not to think about it until later (which is now).  So NASA is out of funding, the CDC furloughed 8,754 workers (diseases have furloughed zero), and the NIH has stopped its research and halted new grants.  So it happened.  But do I dare ask, is this all bad?  (Yes, it&#8217;s bad, but stay with me here).  All day in the lab, I heard people complaining about missing online data sets and publications, government websites going down, grant reviews coming to a screeching halt, and job interviews at the NIH being up in the air.  Moreover, social media has been lighting up with people expressing how they didn&#8217;t realize how many government resources they needed just to get through their day conducting scientific research.</p>
<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/44443a4089b156845e56327dde5346e5/tumblr_inline_mu0pjs4d2a1snsdec.png"/></p>

<p></p>
<p>All of this has made me wonder, will this make scientists get involved in scientific policy?  The popular opinion is that science is becoming an increasingly prominent issue throughout the world.  Yet, most of the policies are dictated by people without technical training, and practicing scientists have been reluctant participants in the national conversation.  Rees Kassen of the University of Ottawa wrote an excellent <a href="http://www.nature.com/news/if-you-want-to-win-the-game-you-must-join-in-1.9580">editorial in <em>Nature</em></a> about this very issue.  Kassen gives an example of the Canadian parliament.  Of the 308 members of parliament, 17 hold a degree in the natural sciences, engineering, or health sciences.  If these numbers reflected national university graduation rates, there would be 98 members of parliament with formal scientific training.  So the <span>burden of nurturing the social momentum of science really falls on its practitioners.  Kassen states that,</span></p>
<p><em>"researchers must recognize that poor scientific decisions in politics do not necessarily result from a lack of understanding. They are, rather, a failure of scientists to communicate their message effectively in what is ultimately a political, not a scientific arena."</em></p>
<p>Moreover, Kassen goes on to point out a few interesting points of view that I think are true.  He asserts that,</p>
<p><em>"scientists think too highly of their own view of the world and fail to appreciate the complex, multifarious nature of decision making."</em></p>
<p>And also, that to a politician,</p>
<p><em>"science is an interest group like any other."</em></p>
<p>Kassen&#8217;s observations invoke a 2004 remark from former congressman Sherwood Boehlert, who was then the chair of the House Science Committee.  As he stated, </p>
<p><em>"The argument that science funding is a long-term national investment does nothing to set scientists apart.  All that sets them apart is that scientists are the only group that thinks they&#8217;re making a unique argument."</em></p>
<p><em><br/></em>What a quote, eh?  It seems to confirm Kassen&#8217;s view that science is funded as an interest group.  So if the members of that group (the scientists) don&#8217;t voice strong displeasure and opposition against funding cuts, it might make it seem that we don&#8217;t really care about the cuts, doesn&#8217;t it? Many more have expressed this same view that scientists need to get involved in policy decisions.  I chose this one because it&#8217;s a gem.  <span>If the Kassen piece didn&#8217;t grab you, how about a </span><a href="http://www.alzforum.org/new/detail.asp?id=1681">plea by Newt Gingrich</a><span> (of all people)!  Gingrich was a keynote speaker at the 2007 Society for Neuroscience Conference in San Diego (I was in the audience). Predictably, he was asked a lot of tough questions by the crowd, but his message was surprising.  He pleaded with the neuroscientists to get involved and help politician make informed decisions about scientific policy.  I don&#8217;t care much for the guy as a politician, but I found myself appreciating what he had to say.</span></p>
<p><span> </span></p>
<p><span>The shutdown is maddening and sad.  But if anything good comes out of this, I hope that it makes a generation of young scientists realize how much government support is require on a daily basis to accomplish science.  I hope it serves as a call to action to get involved and help politicians foster the policies that allow science in the United States to thrive.  I think it&#8217;s long overdue for the scientific community to start educating the public about the values of science, and make a case for the necessity of investing in its development. </span></p><p class="answer_form_container"><iframe
                    name="answer_form_frame_62866005373"
                    id="answer_form_frame_62866005373"
                    scrolling="no" frameborder="0"
                    style="border:0px; background-color:transparent; overflow:hidden;"
