						<div class="title">
							<h1>Nuclear Gastronomy</h1>						
						</div>
                        
						
						<div class="caption">
						
						<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/ea4ad768426c0f86b9bb51fae82329cd/tumblr_inline_mtywe4fGe81snsdec.jpg"/></p>

<p></p>
<p><em>"The radiation left over from the Big Bang is the same as that in your microwave oven but very much less powerful. It would heat your pizza only to minus 271.3 degrees celsius - not much good for defrosting the pizza, let alone cooking it."</em></p>
<p><span>-Stephen Hawking</span></p>
<p><span> </span></p>
<p>There have often been times in my career when I was stuck in the lab without any easy way of getting or making food.  This is the worst.  A long experiment (usually critical) makes for a long day.  But it&#8217;s even longer when you are hungry and irritable.  At these critical times, I found it&#8217;s useful to have a few non-perishable food items at work to make a quick meal with the resources available.  If anything, cooking in the lab makes for a few welcome minutes of distraction between experiments.  Here, I&#8217;ll periodically post some recipes that I&#8217;ve employed over the years.  Remember, all are laboratory-tested and scientist (at least this one) approved.</p>

<p>The recipes for nuclear gastronomy follow a few rules:</p>
<p>Rule #1: It must be tasty</p>
<p><span>Rule #2: It must be tasty</span></p>
<p>Rule #3: All ingredients must fit inside a coffee mug</p>
<p>Rule #4: Everything must be cooked in a microwave</p>
<p>Rule #5: Most of the recipe ingredients must be non-perishable (there maybe special exceptions)</p>
<p>Rule #6: All recipes must take less than 15 minutes to prepare</p>

<p></p>
<p><span><strong>Mac and Cheese</strong></span></p>
<p><span><em>Ingredients:</em></span></p>
<p>1/3 Cup pasta</p>
<p>1/2 Cup water</p>
<p>1/4 Cup milk, or 1 Tablespoon of instant dry milk</p>
<p>1/4 Cup shredded cheddar cheese</p>

<p>1) Combine the pasta and water in your mug.  Microwave on high at two minute intervals and stir the pasta between intervals.  Keep going until the water is absorbed and the pasta is soft (typically between 4 - 6 minutes)</p>
<p><em>Note: The water may boil over during the heating.  If this keeps happening, cut down the duration of the heating intervals.</em></p>

<p>2) Add the milk and the cheese and microwave until the cheese is melted (typically about a minute).  </p>
<p><em>Note: If using powder milk: you may need to add a little water to dissolve the milk, and if you&#8217;re a biologist, I highly recommend that you NOT use the lab milk for western blotting.</em></p>

<p>3) Stir and enjoy.</p>
						
