						<div class="title">
							<h1>Perhaps the worst day of scientific work.  Ever.</h1>						
						</div>
                        
						
						<div class="caption">
						
						<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/33dcf95e4e697335e3e2980adae2e430/tumblr_inline_mttdwhpuJs1snsdec.jpg"/></p>
<p><em>Wheeler Peak, Nevada</em></p>
<p>&#8220;<em>Of all the trees we could have hit, we had to get the one that hits back!&#8221;</em></p>
<p>-Ron Weasley, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets</p>

<p></p>
<p>This story takes a bad day at work to a whole new level.  Donald Rusk Currey was a promising graduate student at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.  His Ph.D. dissertation pioneered the use of dendrochronology techniques (looking at tree ring patterns) to study dynamic changes in the Earth&#8217;s climate.  In particular, Donald was interested in knowing what tree ring patterns could tell us about the cooling of the earth seen in Medieval times known as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Ice_Age">Little Ice Age</a>.  </p>

<p>In 1963, Donald was a 30 year old scientist who became aware of a population of Bristlecone Pine trees on Wheeler peak. As Bristle cone pines in the White Mountains of California were discovered to be older than any species yet dated, Donald was particularly interested in taking core samples from these trees to see what they could tell us about past and current climate changes (rain amounts, temperature, etc).</p>
<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/59bd1d34a3b4e9b9dc823a87af57a824/tumblr_inline_mtyf3lNeS81snsdec.jpg"/></p>
<p><em>Bristlecone Pine Tree</em></p>
<p><em><br/></em>In the summer of 1964, encouraged in his scientific pursuits by a grant from the National Science Foundation, Donald made a trip out to Nevada to obtain samples from the Bristlecone pines.  He climbed Wheeler peak and took several cores from trees on the mountain.  To his delight, he found that their ages exceed 3000 years (How cool is that!).  Donald became particularly captivated by one Bristlecone tree that had such a tortuous look that he hypothesized its age must surpass the ones he had already sampled.  He designated this tree WPN-114, and dug in with his specialized hand-powered drill purchased from Sweden.  Immediately, he noticed that obtaining a core sample from WPN-114 was very difficult.  (Ping!) His first attempt caused the drill bit to break in the trunk of the tree.  When he started a second bore in the trunk with his backup drill, (Ping!) the second drill bit also broke in the tree.  Out of tools and dejected, Donald hiked back down the peak.  At this point, Donald was frantic.  He knew this was the only trip he would make to Nevada that year, and worse, all of his tools needed for data collection were now stuck inside the trunk of a tree.  His trip out west appeared to be in jeopardy.</p>
<p>In desperation, Donald located the district forest ranger office and explained his situation.  Surprisingly, the forest rangers told him not to worry.  Since Donald&#8217;s tree was not a notable landmark, they would cut the tree down for him.  On August 6, 1964, Donald and the forest rangers climbed up Wheeler peak and down went WPN-114, and Donald was able to obtain several slabs of the tree to take back with him.  He began to manually count of the rings.  After the first day, Donald was able to count 1000 rings, putting him in medieval times&#8230;</p>
<p>Day 2&#8230;2000 (Jesus times)</p>
<p>Day 3&#8230;3000 (David and Goliath times)</p>
<p>Day 4&#8230;4844 (End of the Neolithic era)!</p>
<p>At this point, Donald paused. He realized he had in his possession the remnants of a 4844 year old organism.  Until then, the oldest living thing ever recorded had been another tree dated at 4600 years.  Imagine the panic Donald Rusk must have felt at realizing that he just killed the oldest living thing known to man.  Staying true to his scientific training, Donald counted again, and again, but to no avail.  Every count showed that Donald had in his possession the remnants of the oldest living life form on the planet. Moreover, the locals and tree aficionados were inclined to naming the Bristlecone pines in the area.  And ironically, WPN-114 wasn&#8217;t a nameless landmark, it was known as the Prometheus tree, after the mythological champion of mankind who stole fire from the gods to give to humans.    </p>
<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/3c4461e956ff8bb4ffb6d8227bce3d6c/tumblr_inline_mtyhqiI6lV1snsdec.jpg"/></p>
<p><em>Donald R. Currey (1965) Ecology</em></p>

<p>So imagine yourself in this situation.  You&#8217;re 30, on your way to a Ph.D., and feeling good about finally creating a professional reputation for yourself.  Then you come to the realization that in your enthusiasm, you annihilated the oldest thing to inhabit this planet.  What do you do?  Despite all of the irony already embedded in this story, what makes this story truly remarkable is what Donald Currey did next.  He published his data.  I think it would be completely understandable if Donald pretended this never happened, or reported the tree as having fewer rings than in reality.  But Donald stuck to the truth.  He <span>published his findings in the journal </span><em>Ecology </em><span>in 1965, and I think it&#8217;s fair to say that he knew that his &#8216;work&#8217; would cause an uproar.  For example, the Little Ice Age is attributed to have occurred between ~1350 - 1850&#160;A.D., but in the paper, Donald attributes the era to be from 2000 years ago to the present.  Presumably, in an attempt to soften the criticism of why he was taking samples from such old trees in the first place.  Despite this, Donald went through with the hard thing.  He told the truth and accurately reported his findings even though he knew it threatened to destroy his budding career and scientific reputation.  </span></p>
<p><span> </span></p>
<p><span>As you can imagine, there was a lot of public anger in the years following its publication.  Donald never talked publicly about the Prometheus tree.  But despite the magnitude of his error (and perhaps because of his intellectual courage), Donald continued to pursue science.  </span><span>He earned his Ph.D. from the University of Kansas in 1969 and went on to have a fruitful academic career as a professor at the University of Utah, where he continued his work with Bristlecone pines in the Great Basin.  He became a well respected scientist and a champion of environmental issues. When it came time to protect the Bristlecone pines, Donald personally lobbied Congress to designate the Great Basin as a national park. Donald passed away in 2004 at the age of 70.  The University of Utah department of Geography has endowed a scholarship in his name.</span></p>
						
						</div> <!-- End caption -->
					    
                         
					
