				<div class="post text">
				
					<div class="narrow">
					    
                        
						<div class="title">
							<h1>The most human pursuit of human pursuits</h1>						
						</div>
                        
						
						<div class="caption">
						
						<p><img alt="image" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/StoryOTB017_p35_LotFleesFromSodom.jpg/300px-StoryOTB017_p35_LotFleesFromSodom.jpg"/></p>
<p>“<em>And Lot’s wife, of course, was told not to look back where all those people and their homes had been.  But she did look back, and I love her for that, because it was so human.  So she was turned into a pillar of salt.  So it goes.</em>”</p>
<p>-Kurt Vonnegut, <em>Slaughterhouse-Five</em></p>
<p>Kurt Vonnegut was referring to the Biblical story of Lot from the Book of Genesis.  Lot and Sarah were spared from the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah, and on the orders of God, were explicitly told not to look back while fleeing God&#8217;s destruction of those cities.  Of course, curiosity got the best of Sarah, and so she looked back and was punished by transforming into a pillar of salt.  This is the story that’s stayed with me throughout my scientific career.  Not because I’m religious (I’m not), or because I read the Bible (I don’t.  Okay, my parents made me a long time ago), but because embedded in this ancient story is the paradoxical nature of what it is to be human.  On the one hand, we’re hopelessly inept creatures who can’t obey a simple command, on the other hand, we’re fiercely curious beings willing to pursue knowledge despite the consequences.  Quite simply, science is an entirely human endeavor, and arguably, it is <strong>THE</strong> most human of human activities.  It is conducted by imperfect creatures struggling with confusion, errors, emotions, and temptations.  It shouldn’t work, but miraculously, it does and it thrives.  Science works because of two beautiful cogs within our being: our willingness to fail (repeatedly), and above all else, our insatiable curiosity.     </p>

<p>So that’s pretty much all I’m going to say about the obvious: the pursuit of scientific truth is in our DNA (no pun intended).  The drive to fulfill our curiosity reflects some of the very best of what it is to be human.  But I&#8217;m really here to illustrate the parts of science that make you cringe, shake your head, and hopefully make you see that science is really a collection of genuine but flawed humans trying their best.  This blog is dedicated to telling the stories in science that reveal more about our humanity than about science (hence, “science as folk”).   </p>

<p>This seems like a good place to start.  Recently, I read a great piece by John Skylar entitled “<a href="http://mashable.com/2013/09/20/why-you-dont-love-science/">Why you DON’T actually fucking love science</a>”.  In it, John makes the point that science is produced by people who endure years of sacrifice, especially in the face of federal budget cuts toward scientific research.  For example, a staple source of funding for biomedical research in academia is grants awarded to professors by the National Institutes of Health (NIH), the RO1 grant.  As John put it, this is the “I made it” grant, and it is the money that pays for the supplies, equipment, laboratory space, and the salaries of people doing the research.  </p>
<p>The following is a graph provided by the NIH that shows a sharp increase starting in the last 10 years or so for the average age of a FIRST time recipient (that&#8217;s right, first time).  Mind you, these are scholars who have invested 4 years to complete a bachelor&#8217;s degree in science, ~6 years to complete their Ph.D., and ~5 years of postdoctoral training (and that&#8217;s pretty much the minimum).  Why is it going up? </p>

<p><img alt="NIH-Graph" src="http://rack.3.mshcdn.com/media/ZgkyMDEzLzA5LzIwL2NhL05JSEdyYXBoLmJkZDhmLmpwZwpwCXRodW1iCTEyMDB4OTYwMD4/c5e4c5d9/454/NIH-Graph.jpg"/></p>
<p><strong>Source:</strong> National Institutes of Health</p>
<p>Good question.  The answer is in the NIH budget.  The amount of money the NIH has to give out has stagnated and slowly decreased in the last 10 years.  </p>

<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/78dab6a69f5905a9ed26158c50d2d25a/tumblr_inline_mtptrysHDx1snsdec.png"/></p>
<p><strong>Source</strong>: Adapted<em> from <a href="http://mashable.com/2013/09/20/why-you-dont-love-science/">John Skylar</a> with data from the <a href="http://www.faseb.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=aDQlNW4adp0%3D&amp;tabid=431">Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology</a></em></p>
<p>So let’s pause for a minute and think about the implications of this.  The pot of money that funds scientific careers has dwindled over the last ten years, and this has pushed the age at which scientists start their independent careers into the 40’s.  Admittedly, this sounds bad.  But scientists are a plucky bunch lacking any emotions, so they should be able to handle this disappointment without letting it affect their work, right?  Well, let’s look at some additional data.  One of the worst things that can happen to a scientist is a retraction of their work.  Scientific journals reserve the right to publicly strike a paper out of existence if the work is proven to have errors that change the conclusions of that paper at a later date (i.e., fabrication of data, incorrect analysis, etc.).  As science has grown, the number of papers that have been retracted has also increased.</p>

<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/62d4e50271132c076ea2723222623d95/tumblr_inline_mtptutEJkc1snsdec.png"/></p>
<p><strong>Source</strong>: <em><a href="http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0068397">Steen RG, Casadevall, A, Fang FC. PLOS One (2013)</a></em></p>
<p><span>Importantly, these increases don’t just reflect an overall rise in the number of retractions, but the percentage of publications that have been retracted has dramatically increased in the past few years.  So we’re seeing a real acceleration in the number of retractions in the literature.</span></p>
<p>Is the increase in difficulty of attaining and maintaining a career in science related to the recent increase in the number of retractions?  Let&#8217;s see what happens when we combine the two previous graphs.</p>

<p><img alt="image" src="http://media.tumblr.com/5b1df11864f5c787213547c3a4251553/tumblr_inline_mtpujinaHf1snsdec.png"/></p>

<p>It sure seems suspicious, doesn&#8217;t it?  On a human level, this makes a lot of sense.  Scientific research has been contracting in the United States , and these are desperate times for a lot of folks.  Indeed, the wavering support of science by the federal government leaves a lot to be desired, and in the end will hinder scientific progress.  But before I make it sound like science is going to the crooks, it&#8217;s critical that I mention a few things to this discussion.  Science works through a collective test of time.  What I mean is that once a theory is proposed, the scientific community goes to work to test this theory through their own experimentation.  Reproducible results are confirmed and irreproducible results are discarded, thus producing a body of scientific knowledge through the action of group intelligence.  This is a critical aspect of scientific discovery.  So although <span>the rate of retractions is surely increasing, the dramatic increase in the last few years may not truly reflect a substantial increase in deceptive practices.  Indeed, due to several high profile cases of scientific fraud in the past decade, journals have increased their efforts to weed out fraudulent work.  So some of this increase in the number of retractions simply reflects better methods to detect errors, or put in a more positive light, science is evolving better methods of self-correction.  But needless to say, the very fact that the scientific community needs to divert already limited resources to detect increasing amounts of fraudulent work serves to further limit our progress.   </span></p>
<p>I also want to point out a couple more things that speaks to the honesty of the scientific community.  First, not all retractions reflect fraud or data fabrication.  In many cases, papers are retracted because of genuine errors, and often times, the papers are retracted voluntarily by the investigators once they realize their mistakes.  For an example, see <a href="http://www.jneurosci.org/content/33/37/14974">here</a>.  And <span>perhaps most importantly, the number of retracted papers represents just a tiny fraction of scientific publications produced each year.  Between 1973 and 2011, 21.2 million journal articles were published according to PubMed.  Of those, 890 articles were retracted, producing a retraction rate of 1 in 23,799 articles, or about 0.004%.  Compare that to an error rate of ~2% for the U.S. Postal Service, and it looks pretty good.  This is perhaps the most impressive part of all of this.  There are a few bad apples out there for sure, but despite all of the hardships endured by researchers, and the sad state of scientific funding, science continues to hold its integrity.  In short, science is almost entirely composed of honest people working hard to produce innovative work on a daily basis.  Kind of makes you feel good about human nature and for the future of our species, doesn&#8217;t it?            </span></p>
						
						</div> <!-- End caption -->
					    
                         
					
